\par }}\pard\plain \s18\qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 1\tab}}\pard\plain \s39\qj \fi-425\li0\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\tx567\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls6\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {
For many years the plaintiff and defendant lived in a de facto relationship. The family home was a small farming property at Basket Range. The two children of the relationship were raised on the farm.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 2\tab}Unfortunately the relationship broke down in March 2003 and they separated. Mr\~Mayne issued proceedings in the District Court pursuant to the }{\i De\~
Facto Partners Act}{\i  }{(the Act) seeking a property settlement. The matter was listed for trial. Shortly before trial the parties attended a mediation conference and the matter settled. A consent judgment recording the terms of settlement was entered.

\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 3\tab}Mr Mayne now alleges that Ms Robbins, prior to the mediation conference, did not disclose all of her assets namely her full superannuation entit
lements. He alleges that had he known the true position of her superannuation he would not have agreed to the terms of settlement and therefore he would not have agreed to consent to judgment. He asks this Court to exercise its discretion and set aside th
e consent judgment.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 4\tab}
Ms Robbins alleges she disclosed all information and documents required, and even if she did not, the Court should not exercise its discretion to set aside the consent judgment.
\par }\pard\plain \s1\qj \li0\ri0\sa120\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\kerning32\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {Witnesses
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 5\tab}}\pard\plain \s39\qj \fi-425\li0\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\tx567\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls6\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {Three witnesses gave evidence. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 6\tab}Mr Mayne\rquote s eviden
ce-in-chief consisted of his affidavit of 31 May 2007. He was cross-examined by Mr Wells QC. Mr Mayne was an impressive witness and I accept his evidence. Part of a further affidavit}{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain 
\s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ Affidavit dated the 16}{\super th}{ June 2008.}}}{ of Mr Mayne was also tendered.

\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 7\tab}Ms Robbins\rquote  evidence-in chief consisted of her affidavit of 21 September 2007.  She also filed a later affidavit.}{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote 
\pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ Affidavit dated the 24}{\super th}{ April 2008.}}}{
 She was cross-examined by Mr Tallarida counsel for the plaintiff. I found parts of her evidence puzzling. It was not suggested that she tried to mislead me in her evidence. I accept 
that she genuinely held various beliefs; I do not accept that she ought to have held them as will appear later in the judgment. If there is any conflict in the evidence between Mr Mayne and Ms\~Robbins I prefer the evidence of Mr Mayne.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 8\tab}Mr Watson is an Actuary and he gave expert evidence about various superannuation entitlements. He was an impressive witness and I accept his evidence.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 9\tab}The affidavit of Mr McDiarmid of 12 December 2007 was tendered. He was not required for cross-examination.
\par }\pard\plain \s1\qj \li0\ri0\sa120\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\kerning32\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {Common Ground
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 10\tab}}\pard\plain \s39\qj \fi-425\li0\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\tx567\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls6\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {There was no dispute that an Inter parte Summons and Statement of Claim under the }{\i De Facto Relationships Act 1996 }{(the Act)}{\i  }{was}{\i  }{issued by the plaintiff on 27\~February 2004.  

\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 11\tab}On 12 May 2004 the defence was filed. On 13 September 2004 an amended reply to the defence was filed.   
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 12\tab}
On 17 February 2005 copy documents were filed. The matter was listed for hearing. The precise date was not in evidence but I understand that it was some time in July/August 2005. A private mediation was conducted on or about 19\~June 200
5. Agreement on terms of settlement was reached on that day. On 18\~July 2005 the Court entered judgment on certain terms with the consent of both parties and the order was sealed.
\par }\pard\plain \s1\qj \li0\ri0\sa120\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\kerning32\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {The issues
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 13\tab}}\pard\plain \s39\qj \fi-425\li0\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\tx567\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls6\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {The plaintiff alleges that in his Statement of Claim filed in the original proceedings (\'93Statement of Claim\'94
) he disclosed fully his superannuation entitlements. The plaintiff complains that the defendant did not, prior to the consent judgment being entered, fully disclose her superannuation entitlements. He alleges that she had an obligation of \'93
full disclosure\'94 or, in the alternative, an obligation to discover the document that disclosed her entitlement in full as it was \'93directly relevant\'94 to the cause of action. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 14\tab}The plaintiff alleges that in paragraph 8 (h) of the defence filed by the defendant, she stated that she had \'93
a superannuation entitlement with Super SA worth approximately $65,943.00 as at the 30}{\super th}{ June 2003\'94. This disclosed only part of her superannuation entitlements. The plaintiff complained that at no ti
me did the defendant disclose any other information relating to her superannuation.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 15\tab}By letter of 12 May 2004 the defendant\rquote s solicitors provided a copy of their client\rquote s superannuation \'93at 30/6/03.\'94
  It is alleged that what was disclosed was only part of the overall entitlements; the document provided was not complete.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 16\tab}
Neither Mr Mayne nor Ms Robins updated their superannuation details prior to a settlement being agreed on 18 July 2005. A consent judgment was entered on that day and sealed by this Court.  
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 17\tab}The plaintiff\rquote s complaint is that subsequent to the settlement he became aware that the defendant had only disclosed one part of her \'93
superannuation entitlements\'94 as at the June 2003 date.}{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 
\fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ \tab Paragraph 11 of affidavit.}}}{
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 18\tab}The plaintiff alleges that}{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar
\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ \tab Paragraph 14 of affidavit.}}}{ the defendant had an ongoing obligatio
n to disclose all aspects of her Super SA superannuation policy during negotiations and prior to the consent judgment which should have included the defendant\rquote s \'93employer component\'94
 (as it was later identified) of her superannuation policy.  This component included the Superannuation Guarantee amount. Further the plaintiff alleges that the defendant did not disclose at all the existence of another superannuation scheme known as the 
\'93Triple S Scheme\'94.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 19\tab}The plaintiff alleged that}{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar
\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ \tab Paragraph 18 of affidavit.}}}{ he would not have settled for
 the sum that he did had he been aware of the true position as to the defendant\rquote s superannuation. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 20\tab}The defendant acknowledged not disclosing certain information and/or documents but argued that there was no requirement for her to do so either by way of \'93
full disclosure obligation\'94 or discovery. She also disputed that the plaintiff had fully disclosed his entitlements.
\par }\pard\plain \s1\qj \li0\ri0\sa120\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\kerning32\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {The evidence
\par }\pard\plain \s2\qj \li0\ri0\sa120\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel1\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\i\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {The plaintiff\rquote s evidence
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 21\tab}}\pard\plain \s39\qj \fi-425\li0\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\tx567\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls6\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {The Statement of Claim sought an order for the division of property pursuant to Section 10 of the }{\i De Facto Relationships Act 1996}{. The plaintiff alleged in paragraph\~
8 of the Statement of Claim that the parties, as at the date of separation, had various assets. He alleged in paragraph 8.9 that his \'93AXA Superannuation entitlement\'94 was worth \'93approximately $33,526.00 as at 29}{\super th}{\~October 2003.\'94
 That pleading was not strictly correct as the documentation later showed that the account balance was $33,526.00. Whether strictly that was its value is a different question.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 22\tab}The plaintiff discovered the entire document from AXA dated 29 October 2003.}{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain 
\s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{    Exhibit \'93ITM3\'94 of plaintiff\rquote s affidavit.}}}{
 That document included information about Death Benefits and Total and Permanent Disablement Benefits. It contained information as to what his retirement benefit may be given a particular (assumed but not guaranteed) earning 
rate for his fund. Of importance in this case is that the document contained all the information as to the account balance of the plaintiff whether he was going to access that balance or not. There was no other \'93fund\'94
 from which other benefits attached or flowed. He had no \'93entitlement\'94 to any other \'93benefit\'94. Indeed the projections for a retirement benefit were simply based on the account balance. In effect he had no other benefits attached to his \'93
superannuation\'94. His disclosure included \'93additional employer contributions including Super Guarantee vouchers\'94.}{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar
\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{    See \'93ITM3\'94}}}{
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 23\tab}On 12 May 2004 the defence was filed. The defendant responded to paragraph\~8.9 of the Statement of Claim as follows:  
\par }\pard\plain \s37\qj \fi-1125\li1692\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1692\itap0 \fs22\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {8   (h)\tab \tab 
that the defendant has a superannuation entitlement with Super SA worth approximately $65,943.00 as at the 30}{\super th}{ June 2003.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 24\tab}}\pard\plain \s39\qj \fi-425\li0\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\tx567\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls6\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
