\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 50\tab}I make the following findings of fact.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 51\tab}The plaintiff disclosed the account balance of his superannuation as at 30\~June 2003. That
 disclosure included his contributions and any contributions that had been made by his employer. The plaintiff had no further fund from which entitlements or benefits flowed.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 52\tab}The defendant deliberately did not disclose all of Exhibit P4 to the plaintiff. S
he disclosed that part of her superannuation that related to her contributions. The defendant did not disclose the employer component of her superannuation as at 30\~
June 2003. The defendant did not disclose the existence of the Triple S Scheme to the plaintiff at any stage prior to the consent judgment being entered.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 53\tab}The plaintiff did not personally or through his solicitors make any further enquiry about the defendant\rquote s superannuation after the letter of the 12}{
\super th}{ May 2004 from the defendant\rquote s solicitor to 
his solicitor. I find that the plaintiff assumed that the defendant had disclosed all of the funds from which benefits flowed and, from the time of the receipt of the letter and the Defence, was therefore content to allow negotiations to proceed on the ba
sis that each party kept their superannuation. The negotiations at the mediation proceeded on that basis. Neither the plaintiff nor the defendant \'93updated\'94 their respective superannuation material prior to the mediation.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 54\tab}I find that had the plaintiff been a
ware of the entire contents of P4 he would not have adopted such a position. I accept his statement that had he been made aware of the contents of P4 or indeed of P4 itself his attitude to the manner in which he approached the question of superannuation g
enerally and at the mediation would have been different. It is almost inevitable that he would have sought a valuation of the defendant\rquote s entitlements.}{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar
\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ Affidavit of plaintiff dated 16/6/08 at [17].}}}{
 I accept that he would not have compromised the District Court action}{\i  }{in the amount that he did.
\par }\pard\plain \s1\qj \li0\ri0\sa120\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\kerning32\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {Was there an obligation on the defendant to disclose the information?

\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 55\tab}}\pard\plain \s39\qj \fi-425\li0\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\tx567\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls6\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {The plaintiff instituted his action in the District Court of South Australia pursuant to s 9 of the Act. Pursuant to s 10 of the Act he sought an order for the division of property. Section 11 
of the Act deals with the matters a court takes into account when deciding whether to make an order for division of property.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 56\tab}The plaintiff argued that once proceedings are issued, the Act by its terms, imposes a duty or an obligation of full disclosure. F
urther he argued that duty of disclosure is one of utmost good faith. The plaintiff relied upon the English decision of }{\i Livesey v Jenkins}{\cs49\i\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar
\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ [1985] AC 424.}}}{\i  }{
to support his position that each party owes a duty to the court to make full and frank disclosure of all material fa
cts to the other party and the court. The principle of full and frank disclosure applies, it was argued, not only to contested proceedings heard with full evidence, but also to exchanges of information between parties and their solicitors leading to the m
aking of consent orders without further inquiry by the court.}{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 
\fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ Supra at 473 [H].}}}{
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 57\tab}
The defendant argued that no such duty of disclosure exists under the terms of the Act. Mr Wells QC submitted that there was nothing in the terms of the statutory provisions which would lead to the importation of a \'93duty to disclose\'94.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 58\tab}The defendant sought to distinguish }{\i Livesey v Jenkins }{on the ground that it involved an action under the }{\i Matrimonial and Family Proceedings Act}{,
}{\i  }{a jurisdiction that had its own procedures, that ensured full and fran
k disclosure. Whilst acknowledging that the Family Court of Australia has consistently held that there is a clear obligation as a party to proceedings in that Court to make a full and frank disclosure of all relevant circumstances, the defendant sought to
 distinguish those cases on the same basis.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 59\tab}
Mr Wells QC submitted that the plaintiff chose to issue proceedings in the District Court, as he was entitled to do, and so the normal District Court procedural rules applied. He submitted that Parliament had plac
ed this jurisdiction in the hands of established courts namely the District Court and therefore the parties have to accept that \'93you take your court as you find it\'94
. He developed the submission by saying that the parties were in the civil division of the D
istrict Court and the rules are therefore adversarial; it is not an investigative process. The rules, he argued, provide no procedure to file, for example, an affidavit by a party making full disclosure. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 60\tab}Further, Mr Wells QC pointed to the certification section under the Act whereby a lawyer\rquote 
s certificate would be a warranty disclosing all assets. He argued that there would be no need for that in the legislation if there was an over-riding duty of disclosure.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 61\tab}It could not be said that the Act is clear and unambiguous in its terms. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 62\tab}
I do not accept the argument of the defendant. The comments made about the necessity of full and frank disclosure in the various matrimonial jurisdictions are equally applicable to proceedings under this Act. It is hard to see ho
w a court could fulfil its statutory obligations under s 11 of the Act without there being such an obligation. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 63\tab}It must be borne in mind that parties who have been in a de facto relationship may well be in quite different positions regarding the knowledge 
of assets of the relationship. One party may well be in a strong position to know the material facts and the other party in a weak position to discover them.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 64\tab}After a de facto relationship ends, either of the de facto partners may make an application for the division of property.}{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote 
\pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ s 9 of the Act.}}}{
 That is what occurred here: the plaintiff made such an application.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 65\tab}On an application for the division of property the court may make orders it considers necessary to divide the property in a way that is just and equitable.}{
\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ s 10 of the Act.}}}{ I acce
pt that s 10 of the Act does not require that an order necessarily be made.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 66\tab}However in considering that matter the court }{\ul must}{ have regard to the matters set out in s 11.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 67\tab}Section 11 of the Act states:
\par }\pard\plain \s37\qj \li567\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin567\itap0 \fs22\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\b 11\emdash Matters for consideration by the court
\par }\pard \s37\qj \fi-387\li1134\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1134\itap0 {(1)\tab In deciding whether to make an order for the division of property under this Part, and if so the terms of the order, the court\emdash 
\par }\pard \s37\qj \fi-564\li1701\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1701\itap0 {(a)\tab must consider the financial and non-financial contributions made directly or indirectly by or on behalf of the de facto partners to\emdash 

\par }\pard \s37\qj \fi-576\li2268\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin2268\itap0 {(i)\tab the acquisition, conservation or improvement of property of either or both partners; or
\par (ii)\tab the financial resources of either or both partners; and
\par }\pard \s37\qj \fi-567\li1701\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1701\itap0 {(b)\tab must consider the contributions (including homemaking or parenting contributions) made by either of 
the de facto partners to the other partner or to children of the partners or either of them; and
\par (c)\tab must have regard to the terms of any relevant cohabitation agreement; and
\par (d)\tab may have regard to other relevant matters.
\par }\pard \s37\qj \fi-425\li1134\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1134\itap0 {(2)\tab If a relevant cohabitation agreement\emdash 
\par \tab (a)\tab is a certificated agreement; and
\par \tab (b)\tab provides for the exclusion of the court\rquote s power to set aside or vary the agreement,
\par \tab an order for the division of property under this Part must be consistent with the terms of the agreement.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 68\tab}}\pard\plain \s39\qj \fi-425\li0\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\tx567\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls6\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\'93Property\'94 is defined in s 3 of the Act to include\emdash 
\par }\pard\plain \s37\qj \fi-555\li1689\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1689\itap0 \fs22\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {(a)\tab 
a prospective entitlement or benefit under a superannuation or retirement benefit scheme;
\par }\pard \s37\qj \fi567\li567\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin567\itap0 {(b)\tab not relevant;
\par (c)\tab not relevant;
\par (d)\tab any other valuable benefit.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 69\tab}}\pard\plain \s39\qj \fi-425\li0\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\tx567\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls6\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {There is no discretion. The court cannot comply with s 1
1 if the parties do not disclose all the information to the court. When the court considers an order under s 11 it is not for one of the parties to determine what information they will provide. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 70\tab}In my opinion there is an obligation on each party, once proc
eedings are issued and an order for division of property sought, to make full and frank disclosure of those matters referred to in s 11 of the Act. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 71\tab}Whilst the provisions of the }{\i De\~Facto Relationships Act }{(NSW)}{\i  }{are not identical to this Act, a duty of full
 and frank disclosure has been consistently held to be appropriate under that Act.}{\cs49\fs20\super  \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 
\fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ }{\i Wilson v Vine }{[2003] NSWSC 341, }{\i Hayes v Marquis }{[2008] NSWCA 10.}}}{
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 72\tab}
In any event, I do not accept the argument of the defendant that the manner in which the pleadings evolved in this matter, meant that the defendant did not have to disclos
e the full extent of her superannuation entitlements under the normal rules of discovery. In my view Exhibits P1, P2, P4 and P5 were all directly relevant to the issue of superannuation as pleaded.}{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain 
\s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{  Exhibit P3 and P6 came into existence after the mediation had finalised.}}}{

\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 73\tab}Mr Wells QC referred to rule 58.03 of the District Court Rules relating to discovery. He relied on the fact that proceedings under the }{\i 
De Facto Property Act }{were adversarial in nature. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 74\tab}He submitted that there was no issue relating to superannuation as the defendant had pleaded her superannuation and the Reply a
dmitted it. There was therefore no ongoing obligation of discovery. Mr Wells QC submitted that to conclude that there was an obligation of discovery would be fundamentally unfair to the defendant and that the defendant was entitled to respond as she did. 
I reject that argument.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 75\tab}The defendant pleaded that she had \'93}{\ul a }{superannuation entitlement with Super\~SA worth approximately $65,943 as at the 30}{\super th}{ June 2003\'94
 (my underlining). That pleading was correct in the strict sense. The use of the indefinite article c
annot be overlooked. The defendant did not plead that the entitlement mentioned was her only entitlement. As shown earlier it was not her only entitlement; she had a further entitlement that she had chosen, however innocently, not to disclose. The plainti
ff\rquote s admission in the Reply does no more than admit that fact. It cannot be read as an admission that the defendant\rquote 
s entire superannuation entitlements were pleaded in the defence. In my view the pleadings demonstrate no more than the fact that the plainti
ff disclosed the existence of and amount contained within his superannuation fund. The defendant responded by disclosing part of her superannuation entitlements; the plaintiff in reply admitted that as being an entitlement amount she had. It is no more th
a
n that. She continued to have an obligation to discover the fact that there were other entitlements for superannuation. In my view s 11 makes documents relating to (but not limited to) superannuation entitlements directly relevant in the proceedings. Othe
rwise a court, when exercising its powers under s 10 and s 11 may be doing so without being in possession of all of the relevant facts.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 76\tab}In my view even if there was no obligation of \'93full disclosure\'94, compliance with her obligations of discovery meant she s
hould have sent the rest of the document Exhibit P4 in any event. She should also have discovered Exhibits P1, P2 and P5. The plaintiff also had an obligation to disclose and discover the additional superannuation documents that he obtained. He did not do
 so.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 77\tab}In my view the defendant had a duty to disclose the entire document (or information) or at the very least had an obligation to discover the document. 
\par }\pard\plain \s1\qj \li0\ri0\sa120\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\kerning32\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {Reopening of the case
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 78\tab}}\pard\plain \s39\qj \fi-425\li0\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\tx567\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls6\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {After the close of the evidence and during the course of submissions the plaintiff alleged that he had been caught by surprise by the defendant\rquote 
s case. That, without more, is not a basis for reopening the case of the plaintiff. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 79\tab}The defendant gave evidence when cross-examined by Mr Tallarida, that the reason she did not disclose the 
full extent of her superannuation entitlements was due to the fact that they were of \'93no value\'94 as she had \'93no intention of resigning before aged\~55\'94 and that the Superannuation Guarantee amount simply disappeared. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 80\tab}Mr Wells QC during the course of submiss
ions maintained that this was a correct position for her to adopt. I reject that argument. For reasons that are discussed later the amount does not simply disappear. It is the existence of the employer component that is important not what exactly happens 
to it at various stages.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 81\tab}The plaintiff sought leave to reopen his case to deal with those matters.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 82\tab}Affidavits, as mentioned earlier, had been filed by both the plaintiff and the defendant. Particulars of the plaintiff\rquote 
s claim had been sought by the defendant and provided.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 83\tab}Particulars 1.3 and 1.4 of the Notice for Specific Directions were as follows:
\par }\pard\plain \s37\qj \fi-567\li1134\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1134\itap0 \fs22\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {1.3\tab At paragraph 8(h) of her defence, the defendant asserted that she had \'93
a superannuation entitlement with SuperSA worth approximately $65,943 as at 30\~June 2003.
\par 1.4\tab The defendant did not disclose to the plaintiff or his solicitors any other sum or any further information in relation to her superannuation entitlements.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 84\tab}}\pard\plain \s39\qj \fi-425\li0\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\tx567\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls6\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {In her affidavit the defendant admitted paragraph 1.3. She denied paragraph\~1.4. Her sworn ev
idence at the hearing was more extensive. When questioned under cross-examination about the topic of non-disclosure of the Superannuation Guarantee component of her superannuation entitlements the defendant admitted not disclosing the figures but claimed 
she believed she did not have to do so.}{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super 
\chftn }{ T 78 line 30 ff, T 81 line 24 ff, T 89 line 14 ff, T 90 line 7 ff.}}}{
 Her oral evidence on this topic was not mentioned in any way in her affidavit. Her answer in the affidavit gave the plaintiff no notice of such a position. The answer is ambiguous. I accept that it could arguably be 
interpreted as consistent with her answers in cross-examination. It could also be interpreted, if one is to assume that the Superannuation Guarantee amount as \'93any other sum or any further information in relation to her superannuation entitlements\'94
, as inconsistent.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 85\tab}It is unfortunate that the defendant chose to answer the plaintiff\rquote s allegations in that way.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 86\tab}The plaintiff in his affidavit at paragraph 7 refers to having received the annexure \'93ITM2\'94 to his affidavit from the defendant\rquote 
s solicitors on the 12 May 2004. The defendant\rquote s response to that at paragraph 19 of her affidavit is to simply object to the contents of the paragraph \'93on the basis that it relates to settlement negotiations\'94.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 87\tab}Paragraph 13 of the affidavit of the plaintiff alleges that the defe
ndant disclosed only one part of her policy during property settlement negotiations. The defendant\rquote s response was to assert that part of the plaintiff\rquote s affidavit was inadmissible as it related to settlement negotiations.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 88\tab}I note that when the plaintiff and defendant gave evidence no such objections were taken by the defendant\rquote 
s counsel. Why the defendant did not answer the allegations more fully remained unexplained.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 89\tab}It is unfortunate that the defendant chose to answer in those ways. The defendant avoided in her affidavit joining issue with the plaintiff.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 90\tab}It is true to say that the affidavit of Mr McDiarmid contained relevant information as to how the defendant\rquote 
s superannuation scheme operated. The affidavit was a general explanation of the scheme depending upon the age of retirement or resignation of the defendant. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 91\tab}
However, as mentioned earlier, the plaintiff learnt for the first time when the defendant gave her oral evidence that she was asserting that she did not have to disclose the Superannuation Guaran
tee amount because she had no intention to retire at age 55 and that amount \'93simply disappeared\'94.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 92\tab}This point was then developed by Mr Wells QC in his address. He asserted that the defendant\rquote 
s evidence was correct. He asserted that the Superannuation Guarantee \'93benefit\'94 was replaced by other benefits. The Superannuation Guarantee ceases to be relevant. \'93It\rquote s a book entry its not funded\'94.}{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote 
\pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ T 167.}}}{
 As mentioned it is puzzling that the defendant did not clearly assert this position in her affidavit.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 93\tab}The principle which
 should guide the court in determining whether to grant an application to reopen is whether the interests of justice are better served by allowing or rejecting the application as the case may be.}{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain 
\s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ }{\i Urban Transport Authority of NSW v Nweiser}{ (1992) 28 NSWLR 471.}}}{
 When considering the exercise of the discretion the princip
le factors such as likely prejudice to the other party, whether the decision not to call the evidence was a deliberate and tactical decision and the need to bring proceedings to a close as expeditiously as possible, are all factors to be taken into accoun
t.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 94\tab}The plaintiff by his affidavit and the particulars made his position clear. The defendant\rquote 
s response was, at best, ambiguous. However her position was certainly not made clear. I accept that the plaintiff was caught by surprise by the defendant\rquote s position which in my view was not made clear until her cross-examination. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 95\tab}I do not accept that \'93materiality\'94, as submitted by the defendant, was not a part of the plaintiff\rquote 
s case. It always was a part of the case for the plaintiff. The plaintiff relied on the stated amount of the Superannuation Guarantee and the amounts in the Triple S documents to establish \'93materiality\'94
. What caught the plaintiff by surprise were the assertions that disclosure was unnecessary because \'93she did not intend to resign before aged 55\'94 and that therefore the Superannuation Guarantee amount was basically of no value. It \'93disappeared
\'94.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 96\tab}It was asserted that the reopening of the case would cause serious prejudice to the defendant. I took into account the further affidavit of the defendant
. I accept that the prolongation of the proceedings would undoubtedly be stressful for her as well as time consuming. However that is only one of the factors I have to look at when considering this question. The question of costs of the prolongation of th
e proceedings is a matter that can be argued in due course.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 97\tab}There was no suggestion that the decision by the plaintiff not to call further evidence was simply a tactical one. They were caught by surprise. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 98\tab}I had no doubt that the interests of justice were best served by allowing the application.  I therefore allowed the application to reopen.
