\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 103\tab}}\pard\plain \s39\qj \fi-425\li0\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\tx567\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls6\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {The defendant did not disclose any information relating to the Award and Superannuation Guarantee, Leaving Service Benefit and Retirement Benefit. The document (or part of 
it) that was given to the plaintiff stopped at the figure $65,943.16. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 104\tab}The }{\i Superannuation Act }{provides benefits which are made up of two components \endash 
 the employee component and an employer component. The employee component reflects the member\rquote s contributio
n with interest (in this case the sum of $65,943.16). The employer component (referred to as the Defined Benefit Interest) reflects the benefits that the scheme provides that are in addition to employee component and financed by the employer. The Superann
u
ation Guarantee component always fits within the employer component.  The benefit is dependent on salary at the time of ceasing service. The employer component (Defined Benefit Interest) benefits consisted of the Superannuation Guarantee, the Leaving Serv
ice Benefit and the Retirement Benefit.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 105\tab}Mr Watson}{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 
\fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ Exhibit P14C.}}}{ referred to what was disclosed by the defendant as the \'93Accumulation interest component\'94
. This was the employee component and was equal to the sum of the Member Account (member contributions accumulated wit
h interest) and the PSESS Account (consisting of Public Sector Employees Superannuation Scheme transfer amount as at 30 June 2002, accumulated with interest).
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 106\tab}It is important to understand that what was not disclosed by the defendant was information as to 
the existence of the employer component of the scheme, this part of the scheme arising from the contributions made by the employer. The benefits that arise from this part of the scheme do not rely upon the contributions made by the employee. For example t
he existence and amount of the Superannuation Guarantee was not disclosed to the plaintiff.  Nor were the \'93Leaving Service Benefit\'94 and the \'93Retirement Benefit\'94.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 107\tab}The \'93Defined Benefit Interest\'94 was also called the \'93undisclosed superannuation\'94 by Mr Watson. U
nder the Defined Benefit Interest various consequences flow depending on the age of the member upon exiting the scheme.
\par }\pard\plain \s1\qj \li0\ri0\sa120\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\kerning32\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {
What is the value of the Defined Benefit Interest if a member resigns before age 55?
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 108\tab}}\pard\plain \s39\qj \fi-425\li0\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\tx567\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls6\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {On resignation prior to age 55 the scheme provides three options. These relate to what was called the Superannuation Guarantee.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 109\tab}In his report of 6 June 2008}{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar
\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{  Exhibit P14C.}}}{ Mr Watson explained the \'93Superannuation Guarantee\'94
 (SG) and what options were available to the defendant in relation to it. He set out in his report various valuations in tabular form as follows: 
\par }\pard\plain \qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\fs22\ul Option Description}{\fs22 \tab \tab \tab \tab }{\fs22\ul Employer Component as at
\par }{\fs22 \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab }{\fs22\ul 30 June 2003}{\fs22 \tab \tab }{\fs22\ul 30 June 2005 }{\fs22 
\par 
\par Cash and SG\tab \tab \tab   $36,494\tab \tab \tab   $57,478
\par Preserved #\tab \tab \tab \tab $117,622\tab \tab \tab $167,123
\par Transfer #\tab \tab \tab \tab $131,368\tab \tab \tab $195,616
\par 
\par }\pard \qj \fi-720\li720\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin720\itap0 {#\tab Note, these have been estimated in the absence of complete data. The preserved benefit calculation assumes payment at age 60.
\par 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 110\tab}}\pard\plain \s39\qj \fi-425\li0\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\tx567\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls6\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {He explained that an employee has the choice to take the member accumulation cash (not the PSESS amount) in addition to the Superannuation Guarantee
 amount. If a member took that option the Employer Component is equal to the Superannuation Guarantee amount. This option is the only occasion when the Employer Component is equal to the Superannuation Guarantee amount. If the defendant had exercised the 
cash option in June 2003 the value of her employer component would have been $36,494: as at June 2005, the value would have been $57,478. This option would be the least attractive one and fixes the minimum value of the employer component.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 111\tab}A member who resigned prior to age 55 could consider the two other options. A member could elect to take the \'93preserved\'94
 option. If Ms Robbins resigned but decided not to access the money immediately but took the second option, namely \'93the preserved option\'94 she is in effect preserving her benefit.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 112\tab}In this case the employer component is calculated as a defined benefit (as described in the }{\i Superannuation Act}{
) and as at 30 June 2003 it would have been worth $117,622 at aged 60 increased in line with the CPI.}{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 
\fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ T 338.}}}{ In other words, lo
oking at the table dealing with the Superannuation Guarantee the preserved amount as at 30 June 2003 of $117,622 is in fact the value of the entitlement as at that time and when paid at age 60 would be worth more than that and indeed its value would incre
ase in line with the consumer price index. Preserved simply means in this case that it stays in the same retirement fund.  
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 113\tab}The third option a member has on resignation is to transfer the entirety of their benefit to another fund. Mr Watson explained the tr
ansfer option under that table as being where a member has on resignation transferred the entirety of their benefit into another approved superannuation fund. This invokes a different section of the }{\i Superannuation Act }{
and that is why the calculation is different. The estimated value of that option as at 30 June 2003 was $131,368.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 114\tab}It was not suggested that the defendant considered either of those options although she had that entitlement.
\par }\pard\plain \s1\qj \li0\ri0\sa120\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\kerning32\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {What is the value of the Defined Benefit Interest if a member resigns 
after 55 years of age?
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 115\tab}}\pard\plain \s39\qj \fi-425\li0\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\tx567\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls6\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {Benefits are dependent upon the salary of the member at the time of ceasing service. In order to value the \'93Defined Benefit Interest\'94
 a number of assumptions had to be made. The economic assumptions adopted by Mr Watson are set out in his report and are those required to be adopted for valuations under the }{\i Family Law Act}{. Mr\~
Watson considered those assumptions to be appropriate for this matter. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 116\tab}In his report Mr Watson set out his valuations in tabular form. The \'93accumulation interest\'94 represents the defendant\rquote 
s contributions and earnings. The \'93defined benefit interest\'94 represents the employer component.
\par }\pard\plain \qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {
