\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {The \'93Defined Benefit Interest\'94 shown in the table\~above, represents the present value of the accrued benefits taking into account contingencies such as
 death, retirement, invalidity or resignation. It also allows for future salary growth between 30}{\super th}{
 June 2003 and when the benefit would actually be paid; with regard to resignation it allows for the probability of a member taking any of the various options. The projected amount was then discounted to calculate the present value of those benefits.}{
\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ T 340.}}}{
 It takes into account the possibility of resignation before aged 55.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 118\tab}If one were to assume Ms Robbins were to retire after aged 55 the value of the Defined Benefit Interest would have been greater than $87,515}{
\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ T 341.}}}{
 as there was no longer a possibility of retirement before age 55. As at 30 June 2005, close to the date of the mediation, the Defined Benefit Interest was $129,053.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 119\tab}Mr Watson was of the opinion that the emp
loyer component is equal to the Superannuation Guarantee amount only when a member elects the cash and Superannuation Guarantee option on resignation prior to age 55. In all other circumstances the employer component is greater than the Superannuation Gua
rantee amount.  In other words the superannuation guarantee amount does not \'93disappear\'94 at age 55 but rather is replaced in the employer component with an alternative benefit which has a greater value than the Superannuation Guarantee amount.  

\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 120\tab}Thus in Mr Watson\rquote 
s opinion the value of the superannuation interests of the defendant as at 30 June 2003 was a total of $153,458 and not the $65,943 that was disclosed by the defendant. Thus the Defined Benefit Interest (undisclosed superannuation) as at 30\~June 2003
 had according to Mr Watson a value of $87,515. The calculation of that figure can be seen in Mr Brett\rquote s report.}{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar
\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ Exhibit P14A at p 4.}}}{
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 121\tab}The figure of $87,515 was based on the annual salary of Ms Robbins from her annual statement as at 30 June 2003.}{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote 
\pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ T 332.}}}{  
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 122\tab}As can be seen from Mr Watson\rquote 
s report by 30 June 2005, the accumulation interest was $97,043 but the Defined Benefit Interest had increased to $129,053. By 30\~June 2005 the value of the superannuation was $226,096. By contrast the plaintiff\rquote 
s superannuation had a balance (members contributions plus earnings) of $42,513.21.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 123\tab}I accept, as Mr Watson stated, that superannuation entitlements are distinct from their value. The }{\i Superannuation Act}{\i  }{
governs the entitlements of the contributors. The entitlements are paid from the SA Superannuation Fund under that scheme.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 124\tab}Part IV of the }{\i Superannuation Act}{\i  }{governs the entitlements of the scheme of which the defendant was a member. Part IV of the }{\i 
Superannuation Act}{\i  }{does not tell you the value of those entitlements. To determine the value of such entitlements requires the provision of an opinion by an expert such as an Actuary.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 125\tab}Mr Watson conceded in cross-examination agreed that the Superannuation Guarantee amount was itself only paid in the limited circumstances provided by s\~
28(1)(c) of the }{\i Superannuation Act}{\i  }{and further that the benefit entitlements relating to the Superannuation Guarantee do not apply once a member turns 55 years of age.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 126\tab}However Mr Watson did not agree that, when using the formula mentioned in his report, the Superannuation Guara
ntee did not constitute a component of the formula.}{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {
\cs49\super \chftn }{ T 373, T 384.}}}{ 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 127\tab}I make the following findings.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s56 \fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 1.\tab}}\pard\plain \s56\qj \fi-567\li567\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\jclisttab\tx567\nooverflow\faroman\ls49\rin0\lin567\itap0 
\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {The Superannuation Guarantee entitlement had a minimum value as at 30\~June 2003 of $36,493.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s56 \fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 2.\tab}The Superannuation Guarantee entitlement had a minimum value as at 30\~June 2005 of $57,478.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s56 \fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 3.\tab}I accept the defendant\rquote s evidence that she had no intention of resigning before aged 55.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s56 \fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 4.\tab}On the basis of (3) the value of the Defined Benefit Interest as at 30\~June\~2003 was at least $87,515.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s56 \fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 5.\tab}On the basis of (3) the value of the Defined Benefit Interest as at 30\~June 2005 was at least $129,053.
\par }\pard\plain \s1\qj \li0\ri0\sa120\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\kerning32\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {Does the Court have the power to set aside a perfected order?
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 128\tab}}\pard\plain \s39\qj \fi-425\li0\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\tx567\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls6\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {The plaintiff argued that this Court has jurisdiction to set aside an order made or judgment entered by consent and which has been perfected. As the Court stated in }{\i Cavanagh-Lang v O\rquote 
Callaghan & Ors}{\cs49\i\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{
 [2000] SASC 187. See also }{\i  }{Taylor v Taylor (1979-1980) 143 CLR 1}}}{\i  }{
the provisions of r 84.12 are equally available to set aside a provisional imperfect judgment as well as one that has been perfected. That case did not deal with however a perfected consent judgment.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 129\tab} Mr Wells QC conceded that even before rule 84.12 came into existence the court had a jurisdiction to set aside even a sealed consent judgment.}{
\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ \tab }{\i 
Huddersfield Banking Company Limited v Henry Lister & Son Limited}{ [1895] 2 Ch 273}}}{ Rule\~84.12 enables the application to be made in the action itself and not by a separate action. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 130\tab}In }{\i Mohtar v Mohtar and Seputis}{\cs49\i\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar
\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ (1988) 146 LSJS 377.}}}{\i  }{
Von Doussa J held that r 84.12 vests the court with wider powers than previously existed, to vary and set aside a judgment or order entered by consent. His Honour\rquote s comments were made in the context of considering whether or not the p
laintiff in that case compromised by consent or simply \'93capitulated\'94.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 131\tab}
Given the expansive interpretation given to the power under r 84.12, in my opinion this Court under rule 84.12 has the power to set aside a judgment entered by consent and that includes a perfected order.
\par }\pard\plain \s1\qj \li0\ri0\sa120\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\kerning32\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {Factors involved in applying Rule 84.12
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 132\tab}}\pard\plain \s39\qj \fi-425\li0\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\tx567\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls6\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {In }{\i Harvey v Phillips and Anor}{\cs49\i\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 
\fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ (1956) 95 CLR 235.}}}{\i  }{the Court approved the principle enunciated in }{\i Huddersfield Banking Company Limited v Henry Lister & Son Limited}{\cs49\i\fs20\super \chftn 
{\footnote \pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ [1895] 2 Ch 273 at 280.}}}{\i  }{
that whether a compromise is to be set aside depends
 upon the existence of a ground which would suffice to render a simple contract void or voidable or to entitle the party to equitable relief against it, grounds for example being non-disclosure of a material fact where disclosure is required (amongst othe
r grounds).
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 133\tab}The discretion of the Court in applying rule 84.12 is fettered only by the expression \'93if the justice of the case so requires\'94. In }{\i Mohtar}{
\cs49\i\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ Supra at 391.}}}{\i  }{
Von Doussa J held that the intent of the rule was not to alter the substantive law of contract. His Honour
 confirmed that where a judgment entered by consent embodies an agreement between the parties by which an action is compromised, the principle that a consent judgment will only be set aside on grounds sufficient to render a simple contract void or voidabl
e still applies.}{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ Supra at 391.}}}
{
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 134\tab}
As already discussed there was an obligation on the defendant to fully disclose the document P4 (or discover it) and the information contained therein. The question arises therefore was the non-disclosure a \'93material\'94 matter.
\par }\pard\plain \s1\qj \li0\ri0\sa120\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\kerning32\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {Was there non-disclosure by the defendant of a material fact?
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 135\tab}}\pard\plain \s39\qj \fi-425\li0\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\tx567\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls6\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {
The plaintiff particularised his claim in an Amended Notice for Specific Directions dated 7 September 2007. After discussion the plaintiff confined his application to paragraphs 1.4-1.8, namely that the defe
ndant failed to disclose to the plaintiff her true position concerning her superannuation entitlements.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 136\tab}The defendant did not disclose that part of Exhibit P4 which related to the Superannuation Guarantee and/or the \'93Retirement Benefit\'94 and/or the \'93
Leaving Service Benefit\'94. As mentioned the defendant failed to disclose the \'93employer component\'94 of her superannuation entitlements. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 137\tab}The material date up to which full disclosure must be made is the moment at which the binding contract is concluded. Mere relevan
ce to the issues is not sufficient. Material means \'93of such significance as to be likely to influence the determination of a cause.\'94 }{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar
\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ The Shorter Oxford Dictionary }}}{ Materiality therefore depends upon an assessment of the whole of the evidence.

\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 138\tab}The plaintiff gave evidence that had he kn
own about the further superannuation entitlements he would not have settled the action on the terms he did. I have no doubt that is his belief. However materiality must also have an objective component. That is, in determining whether a non-disclosure is 
material, the court must look at the non-disclosure in the context of the case as a whole and it must do so on an objective basis.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 139\tab}It was submitted by the defendant that whatever entitlements may or may not have been available to the defendant the value of 
those entitlements are not disclosed or recorded in Exhibit P4. It was argued that to establish the value of the entitlements an opinion would be needed from someone such as an actuary. To establish the value of the entitlements an actuary needs to look o
utside \'93ITM2\'94 or \'93JM1\'94 (Exhibit P4) and as such the information contained within those documents does not satisfy the requirement for materiality. It was submitted that therefore the information that was not supplied was not \'93material\'94
 The defendant argued that what was not disclosed was information not \'93value\'94. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 140\tab}
Further it was submitted that the information was available if the plaintiff had chosen to go and look up the Superannuation Act. He knew the defendant was employed as a teacher. It was submitted that what was disclosed on \'93ITM2\'94
 was the fact that her benefits or entitlements could be ascertained from the Act. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 141\tab}The defendant argued that sufficient notice or information was given such that the plaintiff if properly advised could have ascertained the f
act that extra entitlements existed. In particular the defendant relied on the words printed on the bottom of Exhibit P4 (\'93ITM2\'94) which stated as follows:
\par }\pard\plain \s37\qj \li567\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin567\itap0 \fs22\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {
While every effort has been made to safeguard against errors or omissions your benefit remains that which is determined in accordance with the }{\i Superannuation Act 1988}{\i  }{
and regulations governing the scheme and no responsibility will be accepted for any error or omission.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 142\tab}}\pard\plain \s39\qj \fi-425\li0\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\tx567\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls6\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {I reject the defendant\rquote s arguments. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 143\tab}First, a minimum value of the entitlement is estab
lished as at 30 June 2003 as the Superannuation Guarantee amount of $36,493 and as at 30 June 2005 as $57,478.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 144\tab}Secondly, whilst I accept that there was no obligation to provide the plaintiff with the \'93value\'94 of her superannuation entitlements (as done by Mr\~
Watson) what is material here is the information not disclosed namely the existence of the employer component of the scheme that was of some value. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 145\tab}The defendant disclosed information that related to her entitlement flowing from her contributions. She d
id not disclose, and deliberately so, that information relating to her employers contributions and entitlements flowing from that. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 146\tab}In my opinion the non-disclosure was material to both the assessment of the superannuation entitlements and also material to
 the assessment of the assets of the parties the subject of the action. What was not disclosed here was information relating to the existence of a fund of employers contributions from which flowed a group of further entitlements.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 147\tab}Thirdly, materiality is no
t confined to that piece of information in isolation. Having not disclosed information that would lead to the ascertainment of the existence of further entitlements a court can then look at other evidence to determine their value in deciding the question 
of whether the information not disclosed is \'93material\'94
. Simply because there are alternative methods of obtaining information that can be used to obtain a value of the entitlements does not mean that the failure to provide the information in Exhibit P4 is not material. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 148\tab}
Mr Wells QC also submitted that even if there was a requirement for disclosure, which was not admitted, and that the information was relevant, there was no evidence at all as to the fact it would have made a difference. He submitted that I la
cked any of the contextual evidence that would enable me to draw with any confidence a conclusion as to whether the disclosure would have made any difference. He submitted that I would have to speculate without evidence. As Mr Wells QC submitted it is not
 simply a matter of isolating a figure for example of $36,000 or $42,000 and simply saying that was not brought to account. It had to be \'93material\'94.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 149\tab}He submitted that when the parties were engaged in negotiation for the purpose of seeking resolution what wa
s at the forefront of their minds was the value of the major items of property, which was the farm at Forest Range and the plant and equipment and secondly how the distribution should be made, in other words in what proportion. The plaintiff was seeking f
ifty/fifty and the defendant was saying sixty/forty in her favour. Mr Mayne basically had agreed with that in evidence.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 150\tab}However I have found that the plaintiff did so but only on the basis that at the time of the mediation he was not aware of the full entit
lements of the defendant. His evidence at this hearing was that he would not have approached the mediation in the way he did had he known of the defendant\rquote s full superannuation entitlements.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 151\tab}There was some evidence before me about the value of the pool of 
assets discussed at the mediation. There is evidence of the division of some of the assets in the consent order itself. There is evidence of purported values in the letter of the defendant\rquote s solicitors to the plaintiff\rquote 
s solicitors of 12 May 2004.}{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ \'93
ITM 2\'94of the plaintiffs affidavit of the 31}{\super st}{ May 2007.}}}{ Some information as the value of the property can be inferred from the defendant\rquote s own affidavit.}{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain 
\s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ \'93SR3\'94 of the defendants affidavit of the 21}{\super st}{ September 2007.}}}
{ There is the evidence of Mr Mayne as to the respective positions of the parties.}{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 
\fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{  Paragraph 7 of the affidavit of the    Para 8-16 were not admitted. }}}{ The main asset apart from the superannuation was the Basket Range property. No dou
bt the parties had different valuations in mind depending on what they sought to achieve at the mediation.  I infer that its value was around $400,000-$425,000 as at the time of the mediation. It may well have been less than that. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 152\tab}The plaintiff sought leave to reopen his case and call further evidence. I allowed the application. Mr Watson was called and gave evidence about the \'93
value\'94 of the entitlements. It was submitted that Mr Watson\rquote s evidence did not assist due to the lack of information as to the \'93value\'94 of the other assets the subject of discussion at the mediation.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 153\tab}Accepting in general the valuation of Mr Watson it can be seen that the value of the defendant\rquote 
s superannuation entitlements as a proportion of the total assets is significant. I do not have to be satisfied of the precise values of all of the assets. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 154\tab}I infer from the plaintiff\rquote s evidence that had he been given the information about the defendant\rquote 
s further entitlements he would have investigated the entitlements to ascertain their potentia
l value. Paragraphs 12 and 18 of his affidavit of the 31 May 2007 show that the plaintiff considered the Superannuation Guarantee amount of $57,477.00 as at 30/6/05 was sufficiently high for him not to have settled as he did. In actual fact the \'93value
\'94 as estimated by Mr Watson as at 30/6/05, taking into account the \'93Retirement\'94 benefits, was actually $129,053.00.}{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar
\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ Exhibit P14C, p 2.}}}{ As at 30/6/03 it was $87,515.00.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 155\tab}Of course the plaintiff\rquote s attitude is not determinative of the issue of materiality. It must have an objective 
component. However what is does show and I accept is that the plaintiff would have taken a different attitude to ascertaining the true position of the defendants superannuation had the full document been provided.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 156\tab}It is not possible to know with certainty 
what course the plaintiff would have adopted had the information been disclosed. At the time he gave his evidence he did not understand the true nature of the entitlements flowing from the defendant\rquote s employer contributions. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 157\tab}I infer that it was likely tha
t had the information been disclosed he would have required further advice from his solicitors. I have no doubt that the plaintiff would have sought to add the defendant\rquote 
s further entitlements into the pool of assets the subject of the court action. Whethe
r this meant he would have obtained a valuation cannot be stated with certainty but I find it was probable. At the very least he would have added, in addition to the defendant\rquote s contributions, the superannuation guarantee amount $57,478.00.}{
\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ Or just under that amount 
as the matter settled at mediation just prior to 30/6/05.}}}{ The \'93accumulated interest\'94 amount as at 30}{\super th}{
 June 2005 was $97,043. Those two figures combined, namely $154,521, was the minimum value of the defendants superannuation as at the (approximately) the time of the mediation. It is likely that the true value was higher. In the opinion of Mr\~
Watson the actual value of the two components (Accumulation interest plus Defined Benefit interest) as at the 30}{\super th}{ June 2005 was $226,096.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 158\tab}I accept that the defendant had disclosed the \'93Accumulated Interest\'94 (employee component) amount in the 30}{\super th}{
 June 2003 document. Thus the $97,043 (as at 30}{\super th}{ June 2005) amount could have been ascertained by the plaintiff simply by asking for an update. He did not do so but he cannot argue that it was in anyway \'93not disclosed\'94.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 159\tab}However I find that his app
roach was dictated by his lack of knowledge of the existence of the other entitlements. I find that had he been aware of the further entitlements he would have sought full particulars prior to the mediation.}{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote 
\pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ Affidavit of the plaintiff dated 16}{\super th}{
 June 2008 paragraph 17.}}}{
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 160\tab}When looking at all the circumstances in my view the information was, beyond question, material. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 161\tab}The defendant admitted not providing the plaintiff with information relating to what was called the Triple S Scheme.}{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote 
\pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ Exhibits P1, P2, P3.}}}{
 The exhibits establish that the closing balance of the account as at 30 June 2003 was $12,655.13; at 30 June 2004 $40,102.22; as at 30\~June 2005 $68,056.38.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 162\tab}It is clear that the account comprised of amounts \'93salary sacrificed\'94
 by the defendant in addition to investment earnings on the amounts salary sacrificed. The defendant stated as I mentioned earlier that her reason for not disclosing the existence of the scheme was that it \'93post-dated\'94
 the separation. As mentioned, this account was opened by the defendant a few months prior to the settlement.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 163\tab}In any event, whether it did or did not post 
date the settlement, that matter did not relieve the defendant from the obligation of disclosing the information. Leaving aside the question of the Superannuation Guarantee information, the defendant should have disclosed the figure of $12,655.13 in her d
efence and should have provided the documentation in the letter of the 12}{\super th}{ May 2004.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 164\tab}
How she was able to run the farm, support the children and herself whilst salary sacrificing just under $2,000 a month remains largely unexplained. Her suggestion that she was able to \'93salary sacrifice\'94 because she and the children were living in 
\'93straitened circumstance\'94 has an inconsistent ring about it. If she was in \'93straitened circumstances\'94 the ability to salary sacrifice for superannuation, in addition to her other superannuation fund, would be diminished. It may be her \'93
straitened circumstances\'94 came about because she was \'93salary sacrificing\'94.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 165\tab}I note that her personal contributions to the other super scheme continued through this period. Whatever was happening, the p
laintiff was entitled to know, as at the time of mediation, that the defendant had close to $68,000 in a separate superannuation scheme. On her own admission the defendant withheld that information. It was not suggested that the plaintiff had any ability 
to ascertain this information from other sources.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 166\tab}However it was information to which the plaintiff was entitled; that information was also material.
\par }\pard\plain \s1\qj \li0\ri0\sa120\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\kerning32\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {Discretion under Rule 84.12
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 167\tab}}\pard\plain \s39\qj \fi-425\li0\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\tx567\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls6\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {Simply finding that the information was material does not without more call for
 the exercise of the discretion. The defendant submitted that such a finding is a necessary but not sufficient condition for the application of rule 84.12. Even if the non-disclosure was about a material fact the court can only set aside the consent order
 \'93if the justice of the case so requires\'94. I agree with that submission.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 168\tab}The power to set aside a judgment must be exercised sparingly and with great care.}{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain 
\s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ }{\i Mohtar v Mohtar }{(1988}{\i ) }{146 LSJS 377 at 391.}}}{
 Factors that have been considered relevant in the exercise of the discretion include the public inte
rest in the finalisation of litigation, whether there has been any delay in bringing the application and whether third parties have acquired rights pursuant to the judgment.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 169\tab}In this matter the plaintiff brought this application relatively quickly after discovering the \'93non-disclosure\'94
. However third parties have acquired rights which potentially could be affected. The terms of the judgment have been fully performed. Some years have passed since the consent judgment was entered. The plaintiff did in this cas
e treat the superannuation question in a somewhat na\'ef
ve and cavalier fashion. However I am satisfied that he did so as a result of the non-disclosure. Whilst it could be said that he failed to follow up the defendant for an updated statement prior to the m
ediation (and indeed he did not update his superannuation information) his attitude was determined by the non-disclosure. I am satisfied that had the defendant made full disclosure of her entitlements as she was requested to do the plaintiff\rquote 
s attitude would have been quite different. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 170\tab}
The plaintiff agreed that his mother died shortly before the mediation. The defendant was aware of the death as she attended the funeral. However he agreed that he did not include in the settlement discussions at the time of 
the mediation anything of value that he may have received under his late mother\rquote s will.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 171\tab}
I have taken into account the affidavits of the defendant. I accept that the defendant has now organised her own affairs as a result of the consent judgment. Third part
ies have acquired rights. To set aside the judgment now will cause significant difficulties for the defendant in addition to the stress of having the issues of property settlement re-opened. It will lead to more expense for the parties and to the stress o
f
 further potential litigation. I have taken into account the submissions of Mr Wells QC that it is not simply a matter of bringing into account a figure for the entitlements when considering the discretion. I have not overlooked the public policy of bring
i
ng finality to legal proceedings.  However the non-disclosure was in the context of the case very significant. It was a deliberate choice by the defendant. The defendant did not supply the information to her own solicitors. She decided on a course of acti
on on her interpretation of matters. She deliberately did not disclose her Triple S accounts.}{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain \s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 
\fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ Exhibits P1, P2, P3.}}}{ Whilst the Triple S accounts were of lesser importance the plaintiff was entitled to know before the mediation the defendant\rquote 
s financial position including superannuation. The conduct of the defendant, however genuine, denied him that opportunity. The plaintiff approached the mediation without the benefit of the full facts of the defendant\rquote 
s superannuation. As I have already found the value of the entitlements not disclosed was significant. I do not intend to repeat my findings in that regard but the \'93value\'94
 of the entitlements as compared with the total of the assets is a relevant consideration.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 172\tab}Leaving aside the Triple S material I find the justice of the case req
uires the setting aside of the judgment. Adding the Triple S material into the factual basis simply strengthens that position.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 173\tab}Taking all those matters into account in my view the justice of the case requires the setting aside of the judgment. 
\par }\pard\plain \s1\qj \li0\ri0\sa120\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\kerning32\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {Does s 8 of the Act apply? 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 174\tab}}\pard\plain \s39\qj \fi-425\li0\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\tx567\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls6\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {
The defendant argued that rule 84.12 did not apply in this case. Mr Wells QC submitted that the effect of the consent order was that it met the statutory requirements of a cohabitation agreement under the Act.  The defendant argued that wh
ilst there had been a consent judgment entered which could ordinarily attract the discretion under rule 84.12 what the parties had done was to, in effect, enter into a Cohabitation Agreement pursuant to s 5 of the Act. The power to set aside such an agree
m
ent is found in s 8 of the Act. Thus it was argued rule 84.12 does not apply and the statutory test is applicable. Pursuant to s 8, if satisfied that the enforcement of a cohabitation agreement would result in serious injustice the court may set aside or 
vary the agreement to avoid the injustice.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 175\tab}
It was argued that the Consent Judgment met the terms of s 5 of the Act as it was in writing and signed by the parties. Copies of the proposed consent order were signed by both parties. Both the plaintiff and the d
efendant sent their signed copy to the plaintiff\rquote s solicitor. The plaintiff\rquote s solicitor transmitted an E-application for the consent judgment:  she did so with the consent of both parties.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 176\tab}It was argued that signed instructions constitute the agreement in writing signed by the parties. Further it was submitted that by virtue of the }{\i 
Electronic Transactions}{\i  }{\i Act 2000}{\i  }{both the E-application and the judgment itself satisfy the requirement of writing and appropriate signatures. I accept those factual matters.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 177\tab}I do not accept the argument of the defendant. The }{\i De facto Relationships Act }{Part 2 governs \'93Cohabitation agreements\'94
. It provides a method whereby parties may enter into such an arrangement and in due course, if necessary, vary it, set it aside or enforce it.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 178\tab}
Part 3 of the Act provides a different approach. It allows a party to apply to the court for a division of property. This, unlike Part 2, can only operate after the \'93de facto relationship ends\'94.}{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain 
\s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{s 9(1).}}}{ Section 10 provides the power for a court to make orders 
for division of property in a \'93way that is just and equitable\'94.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 179\tab}In deciding whether to make an order under Part 3, s 11 states the court }{\ul must }{consider various matters including the fact that the court }{\ul must }
{(my underlining) have regard to the terms of any r
elevant cohabitation agreement. That in my view refers to a pre-existing cohabitation agreement; that is one that exists prior to the termination of the de facto relationship. In my view the Act does not contemplate the signed proposed consent order as be
ing a cohabitation agreement for the purposes of the Act.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 180\tab}
The Act contemplates alternate approaches. Once Part 3 is invoked as it was in this case, any application for consent judgment cannot be a cohabitation agreement for the purpose of the Act.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 181\tab}It would be an odd conclusion to hold otherwise as an oral application by the parties\rquote 
 solicitors in court for judgment and an order then being later sealed by the court would be subject to rule 84.12 but an E-application for the same judgment would be subject to s 8 of the Act.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 182\tab}In my view s 8 has no application to this matter.
\par }\pard\plain \s1\qj \li0\ri0\sa120\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\kerning32\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {Application of s 8 of the Act
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 183\tab}}\pard\plain \s39\qj \fi-425\li0\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\tx567\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls6\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {However, as the matter was argued before me, I will consider the test propounded under the Act. I will accept for the purpose of this discussion (although I have
 found otherwise) that both the written and signed instructions and the consent judgment itself are cohabitation agreements. I also accept that the terms of the judgment are the source of the rights and obligations created by the judgment in which the ter
ms of the prior agreement have merged. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 184\tab}
Pursuant to s 8 of the Act if the court is satisfied that the enforcement of a cohabitation agreement would result in serious injustice, the court may set aside or vary the agreement to avoid the injustice.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 185\tab}It is not 
profitable in my view to attempt to compare this test with that stated in rule 84.12. The tests are expressed differently although many of the factors to be taken into account in exercising the discretions would be common to both.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 186\tab}Pursuant to s 6 of the Ac
t a cohabitation agreement is subject to, and enforceable under, the law of contract. Section 8 is expressed in terms of the enforcement of the agreement resulting in serious injustice as the test. Whether the test proposed in }{\i Harvey v Phillips}{\i  
}{mentioned e
arlier is the appropriate starting point to consider the discretion under s 8 was not the subject of argument before me. It could be argued that perhaps it is not the appropriate starting point. However given the argument proceeded on the basis that the q
u
estion of the exercise of the power to set aside a cohabitation agreement depended upon the existence of a ground which would suffice to render a simple contract void or voidable or to entitle the party to equitable relief against it I will accept that as
 the relevant starting point.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 187\tab}
For the reasons expressed earlier in relation to rule 84.12 I find that there was a material non-disclosure by the defendant. The question therefore arises whether the \'93enforcement of the cohabitation agreement would result in serious injustice\'94
. The court has to be satisfied not simply of \'93serious injustice\'94 arising from the agreement but rather that the enforcement of the agreement would result in serious injustice.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 188\tab}Both parties referred to the decision of Riley J in }{\i Van Jole v Cole}{\cs49\i\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain 
\s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ [2000] NTSC 18.}}}{\i  }{for his discussion about the meaning of the expression 
\'93serious injustice\'94 in the context of similar legislation. The expression \'93serious injustice\'94 is not defined in the Act. It should be understood in the sense in which it is commonly used in the
 English language. I agree, with respect, with the observations of Riley J that injustice includes the concept of a wrong or of unfairness.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 189\tab}The inclusion of the word \'93serious\'94 must mean that Parliament did not consider that unfairness, if found, would be s
ufficient to permit a court to interfere with an agreement. There must be more. As Riley J suggested the word serious in this context suggests weighty, grave or considerable.}{\cs49\fs20\super \chftn {\footnote \pard\plain 
\s48\qj \fi-261\li261\ri0\widctlpar\tx261\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin261\itap0 \fs20\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {\cs49\super \chftn }{ Supra, [16].}}}{ I gratefully adopt his remarks.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 190\tab}When considering the questions of injustice, fac
tors such as the effect on the defendant, the question of third parties having acquired rights, the public policy of matters not having to be re-litigated are relevant considerations. The court should look at the whole of the surrounding circumstances of 
t
he matter to determine the question of whether enforcement of the agreement would result in serious injustice. I refer to all of those matters discussed in relation to rule 84.12. They are relevant to the question of the exercise of the discretion under s
 8. The significance of the value of the entitlements not disclosed compared with the value of the other assets is a relevant matter.
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 191\tab}Taking into account all matters, had s 8 been applicable, I would have been satisfied that the enforcement of this cohabita
tion agreement would result in serious injustice and I would therefore have ordered that the cohabitation agreement be set aside.
\par }\pard\plain \s1\qj \li0\ri0\sa120\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel0\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\kerning32\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {Final Order
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 192\tab}}\pard\plain \s39\qj \fi-425\li0\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\tx567\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ls6\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\fs26\lang3081\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp3081\langfenp1033 {Pursuant to r 84.12 I set aside the consent order dated 18 July 2005. 
\par {\listtext\pard\plain\s39 \fs16\lang3081\langfe1033\langnp3081 \hich\af0\dbch\af0\loch\f0 193\tab}I will hear the parties on any further orders and the question of costs.
\par }}